WEBVTT

00:01.506 --> 00:04.790
You are listening to a message from First Baptist Church, Wichita Falls.

00:05.291 --> 00:14.321
For more information about First Baptist, click the link in the show notes or go to FBCWS.org.

00:14.341 --> 00:18.526
Today's message comes from senior pastor, Dr. Bob McCartney.

00:18.546 --> 00:23.232
Let's open our Bibles this morning to Luke chapter two, verse 17.

00:25.054 --> 00:26.836
You guys made me feel better today about that.

00:26.876 --> 00:28.178
I just want you to know that.

00:29.122 --> 00:34.790
But before I begin my message this morning, I really do need to do something personal for just a moment.

00:34.850 --> 00:36.492
And that is that I need to thank you.

00:37.413 --> 00:41.539
I want to thank you for being a warm, loving church family.

00:42.460 --> 00:45.644
You have embraced my family this week from afar.

00:46.966 --> 00:49.950
It has been a tough week for the McCartney family.

00:50.972 --> 00:58.642
We are grieving the loss of mom, but we are grieving with hope, knowing that she is with Jesus,

00:59.106 --> 01:05.677
and that she is in a place of comfort and peace and rest has blessed us, but you have been a blessing to us.

01:06.818 --> 01:19.539
Every time you commented on a social media post, it was about her, the beautiful flowers that you sent as a church family, and just your personal condolences have meant a great deal to us.

01:19.599 --> 01:24.247
So thank you for praying for us through this Christmas season.

01:25.108 --> 01:26.290
You know, Christmas

01:26.434 --> 01:29.219
is celebrated differently throughout the world.

01:29.800 --> 01:34.608
There are some kind of unusual celebrations of Christmas when you really think about it.

01:34.688 --> 01:40.899
Like in Germany, there is this part of Christmas that is called Krampusnacht.

01:40.919 --> 01:42.802
And Krampusnacht is

01:43.234 --> 01:50.304
is the night of fear because there's Santa Claus and there's this creature that's like the anti-clause.

01:50.824 --> 01:59.997
And he comes to strike fear into children who are being disobedient and all of this stuff is kind of a demonic creature almost.

02:00.057 --> 02:00.938
It's kind of weird.

02:01.539 --> 02:09.810
In Japan, they celebrate Christmas, but Japan celebrates Christmas in an almost totally secular setting and meaning.

02:10.626 --> 02:15.611
Japan is actually less than 0.2% Christian, not 2%, but 0.2%.

02:16.932 --> 02:22.838
And so while they celebrate Christmas, it is done so in a way that is completely secular.

02:22.918 --> 02:28.363
Christmas, for most of the Japanese, it's almost like a second Valentine's Day.

02:28.463 --> 02:31.606
It celebrates love, but more romantic love.

02:32.227 --> 02:39.634
And actually, the preferred meal or the traditional meal for the Japanese at Christmas is Kentucky Fried Chicken.

02:40.322 --> 02:44.588
They eat more Kentucky Fried Chicken on Christmas than any other day of the year.

02:44.849 --> 02:45.870
It's an amazing thing.

02:45.950 --> 02:47.232
I have no idea why they do that.

02:47.272 --> 02:49.476
I'm just telling you that's the truth, okay?

02:49.496 --> 02:50.417
That's the way it runs.

02:51.038 --> 02:53.862
We love celebrations at Christmas time.

02:54.543 --> 02:58.810
But Christmas time isn't just about celebrations, it's about a proclamation.

02:59.451 --> 03:03.717
A proclamation that God says, you matter to Him.

03:04.358 --> 03:07.122
And we've talked just a little bit through the course of December,

03:07.298 --> 03:08.840
about the meaning of Christmas.

03:08.880 --> 03:32.569
And the meaning of Christmas is that God said His Son in the form of a baby, that God Himself indwelled a human being, and that He came to live among us, to be one of us, to identify with us, yet without sin, so that He could die the death of a perfect sacrifice for our sins and pay our price.

03:33.190 --> 03:34.632
That's the meaning of Christmas.

03:35.072 --> 03:36.594
We've also talked about

03:36.706 --> 03:48.197
the mission of Christmas that Jesus came to seek and to save the lost, that His purpose was to come so that that bridge, that barrier between you and God could be crossed.

03:49.418 --> 03:55.444
He came so that we could be set free from our sin and we could have a relationship with God through faith in Jesus.

03:56.225 --> 04:00.369
And tonight we're going to talk about, or this morning we're going to talk about the message of Christmas.

04:01.109 --> 04:05.874
And the message of Christmas can be found in the story of the shepherds.

04:06.850 --> 04:10.334
The shepherds were out in the fields on the night that Jesus was born.

04:10.674 --> 04:18.122
They're outside of Bethlehem just out in the fields, literally minding their own business because they were tending their sheep.

04:18.783 --> 04:21.906
They were out there and it's a perfectly normal night.

04:21.966 --> 04:22.987
It's just dark.

04:23.027 --> 04:24.028
They're watching sheep.

04:24.048 --> 04:36.722
They hear the bleeding of sheep around them, making sure that scavengers or thieves don't come up and steal the sheep when suddenly an angel appeared before the shepherds.

04:37.058 --> 04:42.707
the emotion that we see most associated with angels is fear.

04:43.468 --> 04:47.734
That's the first thing that an angel always says is, do not fear.

04:47.975 --> 04:51.140
That's like their first thing, which it tells us something about angels.

04:51.640 --> 04:55.747
It tells us that angels are not chubby little babies with wings that play harps.

04:56.067 --> 04:57.189
That's not what an angel is.

04:57.990 --> 05:02.036
An angel is a mighty warrior that strikes fear into people.

05:02.076 --> 05:05.682
And so the angel says, don't be afraid.

05:06.338 --> 05:14.507
And then he tells them why they shouldn't be afraid because I bring you good news of great joy, which will be for all people.

05:14.947 --> 05:19.892
For today in the city of David, there has been born for you a savior who is Christ the Lord.

05:21.173 --> 05:25.778
The person of Jesus Christ is summarized in a single sentence.

05:25.798 --> 05:28.101
In a single sentence, we know who Jesus is.

05:29.202 --> 05:31.744
He is the savior who is Christ the Lord.

05:32.245 --> 05:33.266
He is the savior.

05:33.826 --> 05:40.457
He is the one who came to die on a cross so that our price could be paid so that we could be forgiven for our sins.

05:40.497 --> 05:41.098
He's Savior.

05:41.659 --> 05:42.381
He's Christ.

05:42.561 --> 05:45.506
Or the word there is a word that is translated for Messiah.

05:46.207 --> 05:47.770
He is the anointed one of Israel.

05:47.830 --> 05:53.499
He is the one who will fulfill all those 400-plus prophecies about who the Messiah would be.

05:53.900 --> 05:58.207
He is the one who comes to reign, and He is Lord.

05:59.129 --> 05:59.730
He is

05:59.906 --> 06:11.003
He is curious, he is master, he is worthy of our worship, he is worthy of our allegiance, he is worthy of our obedience because he is our Lord.

06:11.704 --> 06:15.310
In a single sentence, the person of Jesus is encapsulated.

06:16.031 --> 06:23.022
And then he tells the shepherds, he says, and you can go see him, because he was born in Bethlehem, that little village right over there.

06:23.643 --> 06:28.210
The Bible calls it a city, it's more just a little village, and he goes into Bethlehem,

06:28.418 --> 06:31.021
or he says, go into Bethlehem and you'll find him.

06:31.041 --> 06:32.262
And here's how you'll find him.

06:33.123 --> 06:45.377
He will be wrapped in swaddling cloths, the rags that were used, not a beautiful little blue blanket, the rags, and he will be laid in a manger.

06:45.958 --> 06:48.261
Now that sounds romantic at Christmas time.

06:48.942 --> 06:49.302
It's not.

06:50.483 --> 06:53.126
A manger is a feed trough for animals.

06:53.767 --> 06:56.370
You don't lay a baby in a feed trough

06:56.802 --> 06:58.604
That would be highly unusual.

06:59.084 --> 07:02.348
In other words, when they go into town, there's only going to be one of these.

07:02.408 --> 07:08.794
I mean, if there had been a dozen babies born in Bethlehem that night, no other baby is going to be wrapped in rags and laid in a feed draw.

07:10.456 --> 07:11.738
And that's where they find Jesus.

07:12.578 --> 07:17.984
And here's what the Bible says, their reaction to all of that was when they went.

07:18.745 --> 07:20.987
Look at verse 17 of Luke chapter 2.

07:22.289 --> 07:23.730
When they had seen him,

07:24.290 --> 07:42.593
They made known the statement which had been told them about this child and all who heard it were amazed about the things which were told them by the shepherds, but Mary treasured all these things pondering them in her heart.

07:43.534 --> 07:53.266
And the shepherds went back glorifying and praising God for all they had heard and seen just as it had been told to them.

07:54.306 --> 08:03.398
You see, the shepherds were the first people to give voice to the Christmas story, to the good news that Jesus had come.

08:03.979 --> 08:10.387
The shepherds were the very first people to tell anybody else about the story of Jesus.

08:11.209 --> 08:13.432
And their example challenges us.

08:13.532 --> 08:15.594
So let me give you a couple of challenges this morning.

08:16.255 --> 08:22.864
Number one, give your voice no matter the size of your platform.

08:22.884 --> 08:24.306
Some people seem to think that

08:24.994 --> 08:28.158
They can't give their voice to the gospel.

08:28.218 --> 08:33.283
They can't give their voice to the story of Jesus because they just don't have a very big platform.

08:34.044 --> 08:45.957
I mean, if I just had a bigger platform, if I was up on the stage like Bob, or if I was on a football field and a reporter put a microphone in my face, or if I had this big, big platform, then I could share.

08:47.018 --> 08:48.060
Let me tell you about the shepherds.

08:48.981 --> 08:52.745
These shepherds had no platform whatsoever.

08:53.566 --> 08:53.906
None.

08:54.658 --> 08:58.463
These shepherds were not theologians or priests.

08:58.483 --> 09:00.946
They were not trained men in theology.

09:01.006 --> 09:03.569
They didn't know all of the scriptures.

09:04.250 --> 09:05.331
They were not wealthy.

09:05.371 --> 09:08.935
They were not powerful and they were not educated.

09:08.955 --> 09:13.521
Shepherds were among the lowest people in society at that time.

09:13.941 --> 09:16.645
They were virtually outcast.

09:17.686 --> 09:19.688
They were outcast in society.

09:20.269 --> 09:22.572
You see, shepherds had to work on the Sabbath.

09:23.693 --> 09:24.434
And in that,

09:24.770 --> 09:32.107
religious culture to violate the Sabbath was a really, really big problem.

09:32.127 --> 09:37.319
There was a sense in which you were unclean if you violated the Sabbath.

09:37.780 --> 09:42.130
And shepherds had to do that because those of you who have any livestock you know

09:42.242 --> 09:48.511
that you just don't take a Sunday off and not just go feed them or tend to them or water them and make sure everything's okay.

09:48.611 --> 09:50.273
You at least have to look after them.

09:50.293 --> 09:54.939
And shepherds had to watch the sheep on the Sabbath so they were considered ceremonially unclean.

09:56.081 --> 09:58.965
And because of that, nobody really wanted to be a shepherd.

09:58.985 --> 10:02.830
It was kind of the last job anybody took.

10:02.850 --> 10:03.411
It really was.

10:04.733 --> 10:05.714
So shepherds,

10:06.754 --> 10:15.527
A lot of times, especially shepherds who were just hired, not the ones who owned the sheep, but the ones who were hired, were seen as untrustworthy people.

10:16.128 --> 10:20.674
So untrustworthy that their testimony was not admissible in court.

10:21.395 --> 10:27.624
If a shepherd testified to something, then it had to be verified by someone else before anybody would believe it.

10:28.786 --> 10:34.354
Now, this is one of the ways, by the way, this is a little sidetracked, but this is one of the ways we know the Bible is true.

10:35.426 --> 10:43.517
Because if you're writing this story and you're making it up, you make up a witness to this who is actually trustworthy.

10:43.557 --> 10:53.650
But what God does is He sends the first message of Christmas to a bunch of guys who were the lowest of society who had no platform whatsoever.

10:54.952 --> 10:56.213
There's a lesson in that for us.

10:57.675 --> 10:59.858
You see, you have a better platform than a shepherd.

11:00.706 --> 11:08.504
You may not have a big platform, but I will guarantee you, you have a better platform than a shepherd does to share the story of Christ.

11:08.524 --> 11:10.509
You know, I appreciate it.

11:10.529 --> 11:11.191
I really do.

11:11.551 --> 11:16.082
I've seen some criticism of guys and girls.

11:16.610 --> 11:22.117
who, you know, after a football game, they'll say, you know, I want to first of all thank my Lord and Savior Jesus Christ.

11:22.578 --> 11:23.920
I personally appreciate that.

11:24.060 --> 11:27.525
I appreciated it when Fernando Mendoza, who won the Heisman Trophy.

11:27.825 --> 11:30.549
One of the first things he said was, I want to thank God.

11:30.589 --> 11:32.411
I want to thank my Lord and Savior Jesus Christ.

11:32.431 --> 11:37.378
And he was very specific about not just a nebulous vague God, but Jesus Christ.

11:38.719 --> 11:40.322
I appreciate that when they do that.

11:41.023 --> 11:46.610
I think they're using the platform that has been open to them to at least say,

11:46.690 --> 11:48.172
I'm a follower of Jesus.

11:49.113 --> 11:50.275
I think that's a good thing.

11:50.355 --> 11:54.661
I think it's a great thing when people let others know I am a follower of Jesus.

11:56.443 --> 12:03.933
While some people would say that's not necessarily a great thing, I'm going to tell you that if you will use the platform you have, sometimes God will open the door for a bigger platform.

12:04.794 --> 12:13.906
There are some guys down at Texas A&M and they're hanging around just making trick shots and doing stunts and they're videoing it on their iPhone.

12:14.946 --> 12:18.431
and they start putting it on the web, and all of a sudden these things start going viral.

12:18.791 --> 12:21.074
And they became Dude Perfect.

12:21.915 --> 12:26.762
And now they're touring the country, filling up arenas, doing all these stunts and crazy things.

12:27.523 --> 12:34.632
And it's amazing, but at the end of every single performance, they tell people that they're followers of Jesus and they present the gospel.

12:35.774 --> 12:44.786
You see, whatever platform you have, God wants to use it for His glory and for the message of the gospel to get out.

12:45.154 --> 12:45.995
How could you do that?

12:47.396 --> 13:02.431
Well, one of our baptism stories was so beautiful this morning, and all of them always are, but the one that got my attention was a friend, Christian, gives Michael a book, and he reads it, and it's about Jesus, and he gives his life to Christ.

13:03.692 --> 13:06.154
You could give somebody a book that's made a difference in your life.

13:06.194 --> 13:10.959
You could give somebody a personal invitation to come to Christmas Eve service, walk across the street.

13:10.979 --> 13:13.541
You might say, you know what, I really don't know that I have a platform.

13:13.561 --> 13:14.322
You have neighbors.

13:15.490 --> 13:22.838
So love your neighbor enough to just walk across the street and say, there's a Christmas Eve service at my church at three o'clock and five o'clock.

13:22.858 --> 13:24.600
You'll be home in time for dinner or grandmas.

13:26.522 --> 13:27.363
You won't miss a thing.

13:28.844 --> 13:30.426
They'll hear the gospel if they come.

13:31.627 --> 13:34.871
Maybe for you, it might be sharing your personal testimony.

13:36.092 --> 13:39.015
You know, it's not so much about being a theologian.

13:39.035 --> 13:41.938
It's not about having all the answers, but you can do

13:43.778 --> 13:50.928
what the Gatorian demoniac did, this guy in Mark chapter five, the Bible describes as being inhabited with a legion of demons.

13:52.030 --> 14:00.282
And Jesus cast those demons out of him and he'd been living in a graveyard and running around like a mad man, like he was crazy.

14:00.682 --> 14:07.171
He ran around naked and he had this supernatural strength almost because of this demonic possession that he was under.

14:07.392 --> 14:11.858
And Jesus cast it out and he was saying again, he returned to his family.

14:12.706 --> 14:18.054
But the Bible says in Mark chapter 5 verse 20 that he went all through the Decapolis.

14:18.134 --> 14:22.200
It was a series of 10 little villages in his part of the world.

14:23.061 --> 14:27.828
He went all through the Decapolis telling others what Jesus had done for him.

14:28.930 --> 14:30.472
You don't have to be a theologian.

14:30.512 --> 14:32.916
You don't have to be able to answer all their questions.

14:34.158 --> 14:37.142
But you can tell somebody what Jesus has done for you.

14:38.744 --> 14:42.610
If you know John 3 16 and you have a testimony, you can witness.

14:44.066 --> 14:55.465
So what I would say to you, the message of Christmas is give voice, give your voice to the gospel and use whatever platform you have.

14:56.347 --> 15:00.474
Second thing, give your voice to global missions.

15:01.936 --> 15:03.739
Give your voice to global missions.

15:05.181 --> 15:10.290
The last commandment that Jesus gave is not in the gospels, it's actually in the book of Acts.

15:11.010 --> 15:12.953
Jesus has died for our sins.

15:12.993 --> 15:14.635
He's been buried, resurrected.

15:15.196 --> 15:19.022
He walks among His disciples and gives them some instructions.

15:19.523 --> 15:22.948
And then Jesus is ready to ascend back to heaven.

15:23.208 --> 15:34.004
And the last thing He says is in Acts chapter 1 verse 8, but you will receive power when the Holy Spirit comes upon you.

15:34.826 --> 15:37.810
And you will be my witnesses in Jerusalem

15:37.986 --> 15:45.494
and Judea and Samaria and to the remotest parts of the earth, to the ends of the earth.

15:46.776 --> 15:49.799
Jesus says, you will be my witnesses.

15:50.840 --> 15:53.904
Now he tells them that they're waiting for the Holy Spirit.

15:53.944 --> 15:54.624
Here's what we know.

15:54.725 --> 15:56.647
After his ascension, then they wait.

15:57.688 --> 16:02.874
And then on the day of Pentecost, which was a feast, the Holy Spirit comes and fills every believer.

16:04.295 --> 16:06.898
And now in the age of the church,

16:07.234 --> 16:15.888
Every time someone trusts in Jesus, at that moment, you may not feel a thing, but you are filled with the Holy Spirit.

16:16.649 --> 16:18.111
The Holy Spirit of God comes.

16:18.572 --> 16:23.139
He makes you alive in Christ because you were dead in your trespasses and sins before that.

16:23.440 --> 16:24.942
He makes you alive in Christ.

16:25.243 --> 16:27.226
He seals you in Christ.

16:27.266 --> 16:29.490
He seals your salvation forever.

16:29.770 --> 16:34.738
He fills you with His power, with His wisdom, and you can rely on Him.

16:35.426 --> 16:39.030
If you've ever made this statement, it doesn't feel like my prayers are getting any higher than the ceiling.

16:39.290 --> 16:39.971
Don't worry about it.

16:39.991 --> 16:47.739
They don't have to because the spirit of the living God who is God himself is in you once you become a Christian.

16:48.881 --> 16:50.683
So they were waiting on the Holy Spirit.

16:50.703 --> 16:51.263
Let me tell you something.

16:51.283 --> 16:54.226
When it comes to witnessing, we're not waiting on the Holy Spirit.

16:54.247 --> 16:55.408
The Holy Spirit's waiting on us.

16:56.509 --> 16:57.450
That's what's going on here.

16:58.571 --> 17:00.734
When he tells them, you will be my witnesses in Jerusalem.

17:01.414 --> 17:02.676
Those were the people they knew.

17:02.716 --> 17:04.818
He said, you'll be

17:05.346 --> 17:06.828
my witnesses in Judea.

17:07.209 --> 17:10.854
Those were the people who were like them and the people they liked.

17:11.755 --> 17:16.361
And then he says this, you will be my witnesses in Samaria.

17:16.822 --> 17:18.725
Those were the people they didn't like.

17:20.928 --> 17:24.272
And then you will be my witness to the remotest parts of the earth.

17:24.292 --> 17:25.634
Those were the people they didn't know.

17:26.235 --> 17:31.502
Jesus says, tell the people you know, tell the people you like, tell the people you don't like, tell the people you don't know.

17:32.964 --> 17:34.066
Tell them about me.

17:34.466 --> 17:35.748
Be my witness.

17:37.109 --> 17:39.493
Now you say, I can't go to the remote as part of the earth.

17:40.975 --> 17:42.797
No, none of us can do all of that.

17:43.818 --> 17:44.659
But here's what happens.

17:45.601 --> 17:46.722
God calls people.

17:46.862 --> 18:01.682
God places a special burden on some people's lives and we send them out and by our giving, by our prayer support, we undergird what they're doing and by our supporting them, we are going.

18:02.722 --> 18:04.364
We are going through them.

18:05.285 --> 18:08.129
Every year our church receives an offering at this time of year.

18:09.031 --> 18:12.235
It's called the Laudie Moon Christmas offering for international missions.

18:12.956 --> 18:16.360
Let me give you just a brief little rundown on what that is and why that is.

18:16.901 --> 18:19.405
Laudie Moon was a Southern Baptist missionary.

18:19.945 --> 18:22.909
In the late 1800s, early 1900s, she was in China.

18:23.130 --> 18:24.471
She served for 39 years.

18:25.253 --> 18:26.354
She faithfully

18:26.722 --> 18:32.168
Taught the gospels, she established schools, especially for girls, because they were not being educated.

18:32.668 --> 18:37.914
She obviously, it was a Christian environment, and so she was leading them to faith in Jesus.

18:38.514 --> 18:40.837
But she was a diminutive little lady.

18:40.877 --> 18:47.444
She was 411, and she was very thin, very small lady, just very petite.

18:49.285 --> 18:50.567
But she was a powerhouse.

18:50.707 --> 18:53.650
I mean, like, there was no doubt, even though in that day and age,

18:53.794 --> 18:55.737
You know, women were kind of pushed to the side.

18:56.077 --> 18:58.220
She was the leader of the mission in China.

18:58.300 --> 18:59.782
There was just no doubt about it.

18:59.802 --> 19:06.912
And she would write letters back to the United States asking churches to please support them because there was no unified effort.

19:06.932 --> 19:13.581
Civil war and famine came to China and it got to a place where there was just no food.

19:14.021 --> 19:20.690
And Lottie Moon, though she was being supported, she made a decision that if her people could not eat, she would not eat.

19:21.218 --> 19:23.581
And she took all that she had and she distributed it.

19:23.961 --> 19:25.964
She bought food and shared it with others.

19:26.505 --> 19:28.207
And she lost a tremendous amount of weight.

19:28.247 --> 19:29.428
Her health began to fail.

19:29.869 --> 19:31.371
She began to have some dementia.

19:31.691 --> 19:33.733
And so they sent her back to the United States.

19:33.774 --> 19:34.514
They put her on a ship.

19:35.976 --> 19:45.808
It sailed to Kobe, Japan and on Christmas Eve, 1912, Lottie Moon passed away because of her sacrifices for the gospel.

19:47.891 --> 19:50.354
And so we honor that kind of commitment

19:50.594 --> 19:52.877
by naming our offering after her.

19:52.898 --> 19:54.520
That's not just us though.

19:54.540 --> 20:00.249
It's 45,000 other Southern Baptist churches who pool our resources together.

20:00.269 --> 20:12.427
And it's one of the reasons that for those of you who come to our church and you don't have that background, it's one of the reasons we're Southern Baptist is because we believe that we can do more together than we can do individually.

20:13.128 --> 20:16.954
There is a multiplication effect when we do things together.

20:17.615 --> 20:19.378
And so we pool our offerings

20:19.714 --> 20:34.914
And when you give anything to the Lottie Moon Christmas offering, you're supporting 3,500 plus missionaries in 155 countries that are ministering to many more times that as far as language groups go.

20:35.595 --> 20:46.450
Because when we look at the world, if you look at a world map, you see these straight lines and borders, but the truth is those are geopolitical man-made markers.

20:47.170 --> 20:52.258
What our missionaries do is they go to tribes and to tongues, to language groups.

20:52.999 --> 20:57.365
They go to a specific language group and that might overlap three or four countries.

20:58.387 --> 21:05.938
Or it might be that in one country we have multiple missionaries because there are multiple tribes that need the gospel.

21:06.880 --> 21:10.025
And here's one of the great things that I think you need to understand.

21:10.065 --> 21:13.710
One of the tremendous burdens that maybe as a Christian we should see.

21:14.832 --> 21:16.274
That there are over three

21:16.386 --> 21:23.315
thousand language groups that have no Bible and no access to the gospel right now.

21:24.236 --> 21:30.404
They are lost without help and without the hope of the gospel.

21:30.424 --> 21:33.688
You've been listening to a message from First Baptist Church, Wichita Falls.

21:34.289 --> 21:42.920
For more information about First Baptist, including gathering times and locations, click the link in the show notes or go to FBCWF.org.

21:43.300 --> 21:44.562
